'''Henry Bell Gilkeson''' (June 6, 1850 <U+2013> September 29, 1921) was an American [[lawyer]], [[politician]], [[Superintendent (education)|school administrator]], and [[banker]] in the [[U.S. state]] of [[West Virginia]]. 

Gilkeson was born in [[Moorefield, West Virginia|Moorefield]], [[Virginia]] (now West Virginia) in 1850, the eldest child of a [[dry goods]] merchant, and was raised in [[Romney, West Virginia|Romney]]. He graduated from [[Hampden<U+2013>Sydney College]]. Following his education, Gilkeson became a schoolteacher and served as superintendent of the [[Hampshire County Schools]] district from 1877 to 1879. Gilkeson subsequently undertook the study of law and started a law practice in Romney. Following the death of [[John Collins Covell]] in 1887, Gilkeson served as the principal of the [[West Virginia Schools for the Deaf and Blind]] until 1888. 

Gilkeson served in the [[West Virginia Legislature]] as a [[state senator]] representing the 12th District in the [[West Virginia Senate]] (1890<U+2013>93) and as a member of the [[West Virginia House of Delegates]] (1883<U+2013>85 and 1909<U+2013>11). Gilkeson also served as the [[Mayoralty in the United States|mayor]] of Romney (beginning in 1885), and the first president of the Bank of Romney (1888<U+2013>1913).

== Early life and education ==
Henry Bell Gilkeson was born in [[Moorefield, West Virginia|Moorefield]], [[Virginia]] (now West Virginia) on June 6, 1850.<ref name = "Maxwell1">{{Harvnb|Maxwell|Swisher|1897|p=708.}}</ref><ref name = "Fusfeld1">{{Harvnb|Fusfeld|1921|p=476.}}</ref> He was the eldest child of Robert B. Gilkeson and his wife, Sarah E. Gilkeson, both of [[Scottish people|Scottish]] ancestry.<ref name = "Maxwell1"/><ref name = "McClure1">{{Harvnb|McClure|1914|pp=208<U+2013>209.}}</ref><ref name = "Munske3">{{Harvnb|Munske|Kerns|2004|p=178.}}</ref> His father was a prominent dry goods merchant in [[Romney, West Virginia|Romney]], Henry and his brother, Edward, were raised.<ref name = "Maxwell1"/><ref name = "Munske3"/><ref name = "Cartmell1">{{Harvnb|Cartmell|2009|p=445.}}</ref>

Gilkeson graduated from [[Hampden<U+2013>Sydney College]] in [[Hampden Sydney, Virginia|Hampden Sydney]], Virginia in 1872.<ref name = "Fusfeld1"/><ref name = "HSAA1">{{cite journal| last = | first =  | author-link =| title =Arnold Trust at $1.5 Million and Parade of Unprecedented  Gifts; George S. Arnold Trust Funds Scholarships | journal = Record of the Hampden<U+2013>Sydney Alumni Association | publisher = [[Hampden<U+2013>Sydney College]] | volume = 57 | issue =1 | date = 1980 | page = 2 | url = https://archive.org/details/recordofhampd5711980hamp | accessdate = January 5, 2015}}</ref>  While there, he was inducted as a member of the [[Beta Theta Pi]] [[Fraternities and sororities in North America|fraternity]].<ref name = "Brown1">{{Harvnb|Brown|1917|p=313.}}</ref> Gilkeson completed a special course in engineering at [[Yale University]].<ref name = "Paxton1">{{Harvnb|Paxton|1903|p=216.}}</ref> He also received further education in Germany.<ref name = "Paxton1"/>

== Academic career ==
Following his graduation from Hampden<U+2013>Sydney College, Gilkeson became a schoolteacher and later served as superintendent of the Hampshire County Schools [[School district|district]] from 1877 to 1879.<ref name = "Fusfeld1"/><ref name = "Maxwell5">{{Harvnb|Maxwell|Swisher|1897|p=496.}}</ref><ref name = "Maxwell6">{{Harvnb|Maxwell|Swisher|1897|p=279.}}</ref> Before 1886, Gilkeson was elected a member of the Romney Literary Society together with his brother.<ref name = "Maxwell3">{{Harvnb|Maxwell|Swisher|1897|p=436.}}</ref>

===West Virginia Schools for the Deaf and Blind===
From 1876 to 1888, Gilkeson served as a member and secretary of the fourth, fifth, and sixth Board of Regents of the West Virginia Schools for the Deaf and Blind, a position through which he familiarized himself with the school's efforts to educate its [[Deafness|deaf]] and [[Blindness|blind]] students.<ref name = "Maxwell2">{{Harvnb|Maxwell|Swisher|1897|pp=478<U+2013>479.}}</ref><ref name = "Fusfeld2">{{Harvnb|Fusfeld|1921|p=477.}}</ref>

In 1887, upon the death of the schools' principal, [[John Collins Covell]], Gilkeson was selected by the Board of Regents to serve as principal of the institution.<ref name = "Fusfeld2"/><ref name = "Maxwell7">{{Harvnb|Maxwell|Swisher|1897|p=475.}}</ref><ref name = "Maxwell8">{{Harvnb|Maxwell|Swisher|1897|p=477.}}</ref> The Board of Regents had reservations about selecting an immediate successor to Covell, and requested that Gilkeson fill the position temporarily until the board could safely carefully a permanent replacement.<ref name = "WVDOE1">{{Harvnb|West Virginia Department of Education|1907|p=92.}}</ref> Gilkeson left his lucrative law practice and accepted the position under the condition that he serve as an interim principal while the Board of Regents sought a more suitable candidate to build upon Covell's initiatives and reforms.<ref name = "Fusfeld2"/><ref name = "Maxwell7"/> Gilkeson believed that only administrators and educators fluent in [[sign language]] should be appointed to serve in the School for the Deaf, and during his tenure as principal, he found that personnel who relied on [[Language interpretation|interpreters]] did not receive "satisfactory results".<ref name = "Fusfeld3">{{Harvnb|Fusfeld|1921|p=478.}}</ref> After a few weeks as acting principal, the Board of Regents reconvened and appointed Gilkeson to stay on as the permanent principal.<ref name = "WVDOE1"/> 

During his tenure, the position of principal included the roles of [[clerk]], [[Bookkeeping|bookkeeper]], [[wikt:steward|steward]], and final arbiter of matters in the classroom.<ref name = "Fusfeld3"/> While he lacked special training for the position, Gilkeson's business experience allowed him to run the schools in an economically efficient manner, which pleased the schools' Board of Regents.<ref name = "Maxwell7"/>

In the summer of 1888, Gilkeson was delegated by the Board to Regents to attend the Conference of Superintendents and Principals of American Schools for the Deaf in [[New York City]] and select the most fitting candidate present or recommended to replace him as principal of the West Virginia Schools for the Deaf and Blind.<ref name = "Fusfeld2"/> Gilkeson tendered an offer to C. H. Hill, an instructor at the [[Maryland School for the Deaf]], and upon Gilkeson's return to Romney, he recommended Hill and resigned from his post as principal. Hill was subsequently appointed by the Board to fill his position.<ref name = "Fusfeld2"/><ref name = "Maxwell7"/><ref name = "Maxwell8"/> While the Board of Regents was pleased with Gilkeson's performance as principal and wished for him to stay on in the position, he sought to return to his professional law and political career.<ref name = "WVDOE1"/>

Although Gilkeson resumed the practice of law and pursued a political career, he continued his involvement with and advocacy for the West Virginia Schools for the Deaf and Blind, especially through his influence as a prominent lawyer and [[State legislature (United States)|state legislator]].<ref name = "Fusfeld2"/> Gilkeson used his position as a state legislator to condemn and hold accountable the officials responsible for the mismanagement of the West Virginia Schools for the Deaf and Blind, and often interceded on the schools' behalf following Hill's retirement due to political reasons.<ref name = "Fusfeld2"/> Gilkeson was displeased with the state's political interference in the schools, and the "multiplication" of positions within the institution that were filled with personnel who had political or business ties but lacked prior knowledge or experience with deaf and blind education.<ref name = "Fusfeld3"/>

== Law and political careers ==
[[File:WV Schools for the Deaf and Blind Romney WV 1880 01.jpg|right|200px|thumb|Administration Building of the [[West Virginia Schools for the Deaf and Blind]] in [[Romney, West Virginia|Romney]], [[West Virginia]] in 1880. Gilkeson served as the schools' principal from 1887 to 1888.]]
Following his tenure as superintendent of Hampshire County Schools, Gilkeson undertook the study of law and started a law practice in Romney; he subsequently became a prominent lawyer in the community.<ref name = "Munske3"/><ref name = "Maxwell5"/><ref name = "Fusfeld2"/> His law office was located on Main Street in Romney, two blocks from the West Virginia Schools for the Deaf and Blind.<ref name = "Fusfeld2"/> Due to his preeminence in the legal field and high standing in the community, Gilkeson served as dean of the Hampshire County Bar Association.<ref name = "Fusfeld3"/>

Gilkeson was twice elected to represent [[Hampshire County, West Virginia|Hampshire County]] as a member of the West Virginia House of Delegates for the 1883<U+2013>85,<ref name = "WVL4">{{Harvnb|West Virginia Legislature|1922|p=247.}}</ref><ref name = "WVL5">{{Harvnb|West Virginia Legislature|1922|p=249.}}</ref><ref name = "Lewis1">{{Harvnb|Lewis|1889|pp=463<U+2013>464.}}</ref><ref name = "Maxwell9">{{Harvnb|Maxwell|Swisher|1897|p=278.}}</ref> and 1909<U+2013>11 [[legislative session]]s.<ref name = "Brown1"/><ref name = "WVL7">{{Harvnb|West Virginia Legislature|1922|p=261.}}</ref><ref name = "WVL8">{{Harvnb|West Virginia Legislature|1922|p=262.}}</ref> During the organization of the House of Delegates leadership at the 1884 Democratic Party State Convention in [[Wheeling, West Virginia|Wheeling]], Gilkeson was a leading contender for a speaker candidacy, however, fellow Romney native [[Robert White (attorney general)|Robert White]] was made the party's candidate instead.<ref name = "TWDI1">{{cite newspaper| last = | first =  | author-link =| title =Rookery Over the Speakership: Mr. Gilkeson's Friends Very Indignant at his Treatment | newspaper = The Wheeling Daily Intelligencer | publication-place = [[Wheeling, West Virginia]] | volume = | issue = | date = January 26, 1885 | page = 4 | url = http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn84026844/1885-01-26/ed-1/seq-4/ | accessdate = January 5, 2015}}</ref> 

On August 13, 1890, the Twelfth Senatorial District Democratic Convention nominated Gilkeson to fill the vacant West Virginia State Senate seat of [[Samuel Lightfoot Flournoy]].<ref name = "WVL6">{{Harvnb|West Virginia Legislature|1922|p=252.}}</ref><ref name = "TWDI2">{{cite newspaper| last = | first =  | author-link =| title =Farmers' Alliance: In The Tenth Senatorial District<U+2013>A Straight-Out Democrat Nominated. | newspaper = The Wheeling Daily Intelligencer | publication-place = [[Wheeling, West Virginia]] | volume = | issue = | date = August 14, 1890 | page = 1 | url = http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn84026844/1890-08-14/ed-1/seq-1/ | accessdate = January 5, 2015}}</ref><ref name = "WVL3">{{Harvnb|West Virginia Legislature|1918|p=351.}}</ref> Gilkeson was elected to fill the seat during the general election of 1890 and served the remainder of Flournoy's senate term until 1893.<ref name = "Brown1"/><ref name = "WVL6"/><ref name = "WVL1">{{Harvnb|West Virginia Legislature|1918|p=350.}}</ref> At the time of his appointment, the Twelfth Senatorial District consisted of [[Grant County, West Virginia|Grant]], Hampshire, [[Hardy County, West Virginia|Hardy]], [[Mineral County, West Virginia|Mineral]], and [[Pendleton County, West Virginia|Pendleton]] counties.<ref name = "WVL2">{{Harvnb|West Virginia Legislature|1922|p=272.}}</ref> In 1892, Gilkeson was appointed to the Committees on the Judiciary, Public Buildings and Humane Institutions, Federal Relations, Forfeited, Delinquent, and Unappropriated Lands, and Clerks Office.<ref name = "WVS1">{{Harvnb|West Virginia Senate|1891|pp=24<U+2013>26.}}</ref> In addition to the state senate, Gilkeson also served as the [[Mayoralty in the United States|mayor]] of Romney, West Virginia beginning in 1885.<ref name = "Brannon1">{{Harvnb|Brannon|1976|p=473.}}</ref>

==Banking and business career==
[[File:Wirgman Building 172212pv.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Photographed in 1937, the [[Wirgman Building]] in [[Romney, West Virginia|Romney]] housed the Bank of Romney from 1888 to 1965. The structure was razed in 1965 for the construction of the current Bank of Romney building.]]
Gilkeson served on the board of directors as the first president of the Bank of Romney after it was granted its charter by the West Virginia Legislature on September 3, 1888 and was opened on December 20, 1888.<ref name = "Munske3"/><ref name = "Maxwell4">{{Harvnb|Maxwell|Swisher|1897|p=347.}}</ref><ref name = "Munske1">{{Harvnb|Munske|Kerns|2004|p=115.}}</ref> During Gilkeson's tenure as president, the Bank of Romney occupied two rooms on the ground floor of the [[Wirgman Building]], where the city's previous bank, the Bank of the Valley of Virginia, was located prior to the [[American Civil War]].<ref name = "Maxwell4"/><ref name = "Munske1"/> Gilkeson served as the president of the Bank of Romney until his retirement in 1913, when he was succeeded by [[John J. Cornwell]], 15th [[List of Governors of West Virginia|Governor of West Virginia]].<ref name = "Munske3"/><ref name = "Munske1"/><ref name = "Munske2">{{Harvnb|Munske|Kerns|2004|p=161.}}</ref> In November 1906, Gilkeson, R. W. Dailey, Jr., P. J. Ruckman, and [[Joshua Soule Zimmerman]] were incorporators of the Mill Mountain Orchard Company, which operated [[orchard]]s along the top of [[Mill Creek Mountain]] west of Romney.<ref name = "CET1">{{cite newspaper| last = | first =  | author-link =| title =Money In Orchards. | newspaper = Cumberland Evening Times | publication-place = [[Cumberland, Maryland]] | volume = | issue = | date = November 30, 1906 | page = 1 | url = http://www.newspapers.com/image/30692038/ | accessdate = January 5, 2015}}</ref>

==Later life and death==
Gilkeson resided in Romney for the majority of his life and was involved in most of the community's organizations as either a leader, officer, or [[stockholder]].<ref name = "Fusfeld3"/> Gilkeson's son Henry Bell Gilkeson, Jr. died on November 16, 1901 from injuries sustained by falling against a piece of sharp iron, which penetrated his stomach.<ref name = "TRD1">{{cite newspaper| last = | first =  | author-link =| title =Heard In Winchester: Purchase of Valuable Mining Property<U+2014>Henry Gilkeson, Jr. Dead | newspaper =[[Richmond Times-Dispatch|Richmond Dispatch]] | publication-place = [[Richmond, Virginia]] | volume = | issue = | date = November 17, 1901 | page = 26 | url =http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85038614/1901-11-17/ed-1/seq-26/ | accessdate = January 5, 2015}}</ref><ref name = "HH1">{{cite web | url = http://www.historichampshire.org/test/cems/D-Kindianmnd.htm | title = Indian Mound Cemetery: D-K Listing for All Sections | work = HistoricHampshire.org | publisher = HistoricHampshire.org, Charles C. Hall | accessdate = January 5, 2015}}</ref> Gilkeson's wife, Mary Katherine, predeceased him in February 1910 following the effects of a surgical procedure she had undergone in [[Cumberland, Maryland]].<ref name = "HH1"/><ref name = "TWES1">{{cite newspaper| last = | first =  | author-link =| title =Valley of Virginia | newspaper =[[The Washington Star|Washington Evening Star]] | publication-place = [[Washington, D.C.]] | volume = | issue = | date = February 13, 1910 | page = 15 | url =http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83045462/1910-02-13/ed-1/seq-15/ | accessdate = January 5, 2015}}</ref>

In his later years, Gilkeson suffered from [[allergic rhinitis]] and experienced a "physical breakdown" following the death of his son, Robert William Gilkeson, on October 2, 1918, during the [[Meuse-Argonne Offensive]] of World War I and shortly before the [[Armistice with Germany]].<ref name = "Fusfeld1"/> Robert William Gilkeson was a [[second lieutenant]] in Company C of the 316 Engineers, and was interred in the [[Meuse-Argonne American Cemetery and Memorial]] near [[Romagne-sous-Montfaucon]].<ref name = "HH1"/> Robert William Gilkeson was a 1907 graduate of his father's alma mater, Hampden<U+2013>Sydney College.<ref name = "HSAA1"/>

On account of his increasingly failing health, Gilkeson spent the summer of 1921 in [[Mountain Lake Park, Maryland|Mountain Lake Park]], [[Maryland]] to recuperate.<ref name = "Fusfeld1"/> About a week before his death, Gilkeson fell down a flight of porch steps at his vacation residence, fracturing a number of bones.<ref name = "Fusfeld1"/> He died on September 29, 1921, in Mountain Lake Park and his funeral was held on the anniversary of his son's death on October 2, 1921.<ref name = "Fusfeld1"/> Gilkeson is [[Burial|interred]] with his wife Mary Katherine and son Henry, Jr. at [[Indian Mound Cemetery]] in Romney, West Virginia.<ref name = "HH1"/>

In recounting Gilkeson's achievements to the Conference of Superintendents and Principals of American Schools for the Deaf following his death, West Virginia Schools for the Deaf and Blind instructor Charles D. Seaton said of Gilkeson:<ref name = "Fusfeld4">{{Harvnb|Fusfeld|1921|pp=478<U+2013>479.}}</ref>

{{quote box
|width     = 50em
|border    = 1px
|align     = center
|bgcolor   = #c6dbf7
|halign    = left
|quote     = "His learning ability and integrity were recognized in the various courts in which he practised. As a counselor he was safe, careful, painstaking, and always conscientious. As a criminal lawyer he defended the interests of his clients with all his energy, never however beyond the bounds of honor or of the ethics of his profession. His courtesy to the court, to his associates at the bar, and to witnesses was always such as to place upon him the unerasable stamp of 'gentleman'. His decisions were always based on one proposition &ndash; the right. He was not aggressive. He was unobtrusive in manner, but firm as a rock in his conception of duty. It was a blessed privilege for any young man to have been associated with him and to have been influenced by him as one was bound to be".
|source    =&nbsp;<U+2014> Charles D. Seaton, Conference of Superintendents and Principals of American Schools for the Deaf (1921)
}}

In 1980, Gilkeson's son-in-law George Sloan Arnold bequeathed the $1.5-million George S. Arnold Trust to Hampden<U+2013>Sydney College, his shared alma mater with his father-in-law and brother-in-law Robert William Gilkeson.<ref name = "HSAA1"/> At the time, it was the largest amount given by a living person and the institution's second-largest gift in its 204-year history.<ref name = "HSAA1"/> Arnold gave the trust in honor of the Gilkeson family.<ref name = "HSAA1"/>

