}}

==Religious activities==
Gilkeson was active in the [[Presbyterianism|Presbyterian Church]] in Hampshire County and served as a trustee for the [[Presbyterian polity#Presbytery|Presbytery]] of Winchester along with Samuel Lightfoot Flournoy.<ref name = "Paxton1"/><ref name = "Woodworth1">{{Harvnb|Woodworth|1947|p=369.}}</ref> In 1881, Gilkeson and his fellow trustees were instrumental in securing from Amos L. and Allie G. Pugh a house and a large, partially wooded land lot in [[Capon Bridge, West Virginia|Capon Bridge]] for use by the Presbytery as a centrally located [[manse]] in Hampshire County.<ref name = "Woodworth1"/> Gilkeson remained a trustee of the Presbytery from 1876 until his death in 1921.<ref name = "Woodworth2">{{Harvnb|Woodworth|1947|p=385.}}</ref> He was also a commissioner of the General Assembly of the [[Presbyterian Church in the United States]] representing the Presbytery of Winchester, and attended the assembly's meeting in [[Jackson, Mississippi]], May 15<U+2013>25, 1902.<ref name = "Paxton1"/><ref name = "TT1">{{cite newspaper| last = | first =  | author-link =| title =The General Assembly. | newspaper = The Times | publication-place = [[Richmond, Virginia]] | volume = | issue = | date = May 4, 1902 | page = 14 | url = http://www.newspapers.com/image/80950422/ | accessdate = January 5, 2015}}</ref> 

==Marriage and family==
Gilkeson married on November 19, 1884 to Mary Katherine Paxton (1853<U+2013>1910), daughter of Jordan J. and E. J. Paxton of [[Iron Gate, Virginia]].<ref name = "Maxwell1"/><ref name = "HH1"/><ref name = "TWES1"/><ref name = "TWES2">{{cite newspaper| last = | first =  | author-link =| title =Three Weddings Yesterday | newspaper =[[The Washington Star|Washington Evening Star]] | publication-place = [[Washington, D.C.]] | volume = | issue = | date = November 19, 1884 | page = 1 | url =http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83045462/1884-11-19/ed-1/seq-1/ | accessdate = January 5, 2015}}</ref> Their wedding ceremony was officiated by Reverend George W. Finley of Romney at the residence of [[Mary Ann Lipscomb]] at 1537 I Street, N.W. in [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref name = "TWES2"/> Mary Katherine had been employed as a teacher under Lipscomb at Waverly Seminary.<ref name = "TWES2"/> Following the ceremony, Gilkeson and his wife embarked upon a tour of the [[Northern United States]].<ref name = "TWES2"/> Gilkeson and his wife Mary Katherine had three children together:<ref name = "Maxwell1"/><ref name = "Paxton1"/>
*Laura Paxton Gilkeson Arnold (August 18, 1885 <U+2013> 1973), married Romney lawyer George Sloan Arnold (1885<U+2013>1986)<ref name = "HH2">{{cite web | url = http://www.historichampshire.org/test/cems/A-Cindianmnd.htm | title = Indian Mound Cemetery: A-C Names for all Sections | work = HistoricHampshire.org | publisher = HistoricHampshire.org, Charles C. Hall | accessdate = January 5, 2015}}</ref><ref name = "WVDCH1">{{Cite web | url = http://www.wvculture.org/vrr/va_bcdetail.aspx?Id=2571251 | title = Birth Record Detail: Laura P. Gilkeson | work = West Virginia Vital Research Records | publisher = West Virginia Division of Culture and History | accessdate = January 5, 2015}}</ref>
*Robert William Gilkeson (July 25, 1887 <U+2013> October 2, 1918)<ref name = "Fusfeld1"/><ref name = "HH1"/>
*Henry Bell Gilkeson, Jr. (February 8, 1890 <U+2013> November 16, 1901)<ref name = "HH1"/><ref name = "TRD1"/><ref name = "WVDCH2">{{Cite web | url = http://www.wvculture.org/vrr/va_bcdetail.aspx?Id=2571972 | title = Birth Record Detail: Henry B. Gilkeson | work = West Virginia Vital Research Records | publisher = West Virginia Division of Culture and History | accessdate = January 5, 2015}}</ref>

